The week\'92s immigration and citizenship decisions showed how the state was sorting people into hierarchies of belonging. On June 5, Trump signed a new travel ban that fully barred entry from twelve countries and partially restricted travel from seven more, reviving and expanding the bans of his first term. A separate proclamation suspended Harvard from the student visa program, effectively banning new foreign students from attending and threatening to revoke visas of some who were already there. The administration framed both moves as security measures, linking them rhetorically to a firebomb attack on a pro-Israel rally in Boulder. But the effect was to mark entire nationalities and one university as suspect, regardless of individual conduct. Veterans who had served alongside Afghan translators saw those allies cut off from refuge. International students, long a source of soft power and scientific exchange, became bargaining chips in a domestic feud with an elite institution.\
\
At the same time, the Supreme Court allowed the administration to end humanitarian paroles for roughly half a million people from Cuba, Haiti, Nicaragua, and Venezuela while litigation continued. Those individuals, many of whom had built lives under legal status, were suddenly rendered undocumented and subject to deportation. Lower courts did push back in specific cases, ordering the return of wrongly deported individuals and blocking the removal of families and detainees who had been denied hearings. Yet the overall direction of policy was unmistakable. Citizenship and legal presence were being made more precarious for those from certain countries and backgrounds, while the executive claimed ever broader discretion to decide who could enter, stay, or be expelled. Legal status became a revocable favor.\
\
Immigration enforcement on the ground reflected that discretion in its harshest form. On June 3, ICE officers arrested more than 2,200 people in a single day, the highest number of immigration arrests ever recorded in twenty-four hours. Internal emails urged agents to \'93turn the creative knob up to 11,\'94 encouraging \'93collateral\'94 arrests of anyone encountered during operations, even without warrants. People enrolled in alternatives-to-detention programs were detained when they showed up for scheduled check-ins. A restaurant raid in San Diego ended with flash-bang grenades used against a protesting crowd. In New York, federal officers entered Representative Jerry Nadler\'92s office and handcuffed an aide under the guise of a \'93safety check,\'94 an incident widely seen as an attempt to intimidate a prominent critic. In Los Angeles, the president deployed National Guard and Marine Corps units to suppress mostly peaceful protests against deportations. These were not isolated missteps. They were the visible edge of a system in which security forces were increasingly aligned with the preservation of executive priorities rather than the neutral protection of the public.\
\
The arrest of David Huerta, president of the SEIU of California, during an immigration raid at a garment factory, brought that alignment into sharper relief. Video showed officers using force against Huerta, who was hospitalized, yet the Department of Homeland Security insisted he had assaulted law enforcement. The charges\'97conspiracy to impede an officer\'97carried the weight of criminal law, but the context was a labor leader challenging deportation policies. In Newark, Mayor Ras Baraka filed suit against federal officials for false arrest and malicious prosecution after Homeland Security agents detained him at a protest. Together, these episodes suggested that law enforcement tools were being used not only to police borders but to send a message to those who organize against the administration\'92s agenda: your status, your office, even your body will not shield you. The chill was the point.\
