While the state hardened its stance toward immigrants, protesters, and the poor, it extended mercy and protection to a different group. On January 20, Trump had issued \'93full, complete and unconditional\'94 pardons to roughly 1,500 people charged in connection with the January 6 attack on the Capitol, including those convicted of violent acts. He commuted sentences in additional cases and ordered the Justice Department to dismiss all remaining indictments. In Week 20, the administration went further, firing or sidelining the prosecutors who had handled those cases and disbanding the Capitol siege section. At the same time, Enrique Tarrio and other January 6 figures filed a lawsuit challenging the integrity of their prosecutions. The combined effect was to recast an attack on the peaceful transfer of power as a wrong done to loyalists, and to signal that political violence in service of the regime would be forgiven, even honored, while nonviolent resistance to its policies would be met with raids and charges. Accountability became a matter of allegiance.\
\
Information and memory were adjusted to fit this new order. The president used his social media platform to amplify a conspiracy theory that Joe Biden had been executed in 2020 and replaced by clones or robotic doubles, borrowing language from fringe movements. The Defense Department quietly removed Jackie Robinson\'92s biography from its website. The Navy, on orders from Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth, stripped Harvey Milk\'92s name from a ship during Pride month, in the name of restoring \'93warrior culture.\'94 At the Department of Veterans Affairs, political appointees required doctors and scientists to seek clearance before publishing research, after some had warned that staff cuts were endangering veterans\'92 health. At the Pentagon, press briefings ceased and doors to the briefing room were reportedly locked. In education, Secretary Linda McMahon told Congress she was unsure whether teaching about the Tulsa race massacre, Ruby Bridges, or the accurate results of the 2020 election would violate the administration\'92s policies against diversity, equity, and inclusion. These were not yet full erasures, but they were signals. Certain histories, identities, and facts were being pushed to the margins of official life. The public record was being trimmed to fit the moment.\
