The economic sphere showed how closely policy now tracked the interests and conflicts of a small elite. The feud between Trump and Elon Musk laid bare the degree to which state capacity had been fused with a single oligarch. Musk had been placed at the center of DOGE and enjoyed vast federal contracts for SpaceX. When he criticized the administration\'92s spending bill, Trump publicly suggested that canceling Musk\'92s subsidies and contracts would save billions, and claimed he had asked Musk to leave his role. Musk responded by threatening to decommission the Dragon spacecraft that supply the International Space Station. NASA\'92s operations, and by extension international space cooperation, were suddenly hostage to a personal quarrel. At the same time, a Popular Information investigation revealed that an investment arm of the United Arab Emirates had used a Trump-family-backed stablecoin, USD1, to move $2 billion into Binance. Senate Democrats who advanced the GENIUS Act, a stablecoin bill that could benefit USD1, had received millions from crypto donors. In this environment, the line between public economic policy and private enrichment grew thin. Money and law moved together.\
