Religion and identity were drawn into this struggle over legitimacy. Representative Mary Miller of Illinois posted, then deleted, a message calling it \'93deeply troubling\'94 that a Sikh Granthi had led the morning prayer in the House, mistakenly identifying him as Muslim. Her comments drew rebukes from both parties and from Sikh organizations, but they also reflected a current in which non-Christian faiths are cast as alien to the nation\'92s civic rituals. In West Virginia, a prosecutor suggested that women should report miscarriages to the police under a strict abortion ban, blurring the line between medical care and criminal investigation. The administration rescinded Biden-era guidance that had required hospitals to perform emergency abortions under federal law, even in states with bans, and proposed deep cuts to programs that support poor women and children. These moves together signaled a narrowing of who counts as a full moral subject in the eyes of the state, and whose suffering is treated as an acceptable cost. Some lives were framed as expendable.\
