Against this backdrop, there were still acts of resistance and repair. NPR and several public radio stations filed suit to block the executive order cutting funding to media the president deemed \'93biased,\'94 arguing that it violated the First Amendment. Dominion Voting Systems pressed ahead with its defamation trial against Mike Lindell, seeking accountability for lies about the 2020 election. Federal judges ordered the return of wrongly deported migrants and blocked the deportation of a suspect\'92s family in Colorado until they could seek asylum. A federal appeals court struck down San Diego\'92s yoga ban as unconstitutional. Senator Angus King and Representative Jamie Raskin invoked Margaret Chase Smith\'92s 1950 \'93Declaration of Conscience\'94 to warn against fear-based politics and the concentration of power in the executive. Senator Elizabeth Warren released a report detailing Elon Musk\'92s wealth gains and alleged influence over federal policy. These efforts did not reverse the week\'92s structural shifts, but they kept alive the idea that law and institutions could still serve as limits, not only as weapons. The counter-story remained on the record.\
